Anthropometry and Hb of pregnant and lactating women (PLW)
Minimum Dietary Diversity for Pregnant and Lactating Woman (PLW)

Please describe the foods (meals and snacks) that you ate or drank yesterday during the day and night, whether at home or outside the home. Start with the first food or drink eaten in the morning. Write down all food and drinks mentioned. When composite dishes are mentioned, ask for the list of ingredients. When the respondent has finished, probe for meals and snacks not mentioned.

Foods made from grains: Porridge, bread, rice, pasta/noodles or other foods made from grains e.g corn/maize, wheat, sorghum, millet or any other grains or foods made from these (e.g. bread, noodles, porridge or siwayoon, double roti, chapati, geeh wara paratha)
Foods made from grains: White roots, tubers and plantains White potatoes, white yams, manioc/cassava/yucca, cocoyam, taro or other foods made from white-fleshed roots or tubers or plantains.
Foods made from grains: Pulses (beans, peas and lentils) Mature beans or peas (fresh or dried seed), lentils or bean/pea products, including hummus, tofu and tempeh
Foods made from grains: Nuts and seeds Any tree nut, groundnut/peanut or certain seeds, or nuts/seeds “butters” or pastes
Foods made from grains: Milk and milk products Milk, cheese, yogurt or other milk products but NOT including butter, ice cream, cream or sour cream
Foods made from grains: Organ meat Liver, kidney, heart or other organ meats or blood-based foods
Foods made from grains: Meat and poultry Beef, lamb, goat, rabbit, deer, chicken, duck, or other birds (i.e. partridge, quail, houbara bustard and mallard etc)
Foods made from grains: Fish and seafood Fish or dried fish or shellfish or prawns
Foods made from grains: Eggs Eggs from poultry or any other bird (chicken, duck, guinea fowl etc)

Dark green leafy vegetables Dark green/leafy vegetables, including wild/foraged leaves (such as kale, spinach mustered leaves, cauliflower, Mareero, green garlic, field Foods made from grains: mint, chiber, mitera, etc).

Foods made from grains: Vitamin A rich vegetables, roots and tubers Pumpkin, carrots, squash, or sweet potatoes that are orange inside + other locally available vitamin A rich vegetables (e.g. red sweet pepper, colocasia leaves, coriander leaves, onion leaves, fenugreek leaves, capsicum, cabbage, cucumber, okra, turnip, beet root etc)

Foods made from grains: Vitamin A rich fruits Ripe mangoes, ripe papaya, cantaloupe, apricots (fresh or dried), peaches + other locally available vitamin A rich fruits (e.g. fruiter, oranges, water melon, plum, figs, sapota, pear, strawberry, blue berries, guava, pomegranate, peaches etc)
Foods made from grains: Other vegetables Other vegetables (e.g. tomato, onion, eggplant, cucurbit, ridge, gourd, broccoli, etc), including wild vegetables
Foods made from grains: Other fruits Other fruits, including wild fruits (i.e. dates, black berry, mulberry, banana, apple, grapes and Lesoona etc).

Foods made from grains: Condiments, spices and seasonings Ingredients used in small quantities for flavour, such as chilies, spices, herbs, fish powder, tomato paste, flavour cubes or seeds, black pepper, condiments (soy sauce, hot sauce).
Foods made from grains: Other beverages and foods Tea or coffe if not sweetened, clear broth, alcohol
Foods made from grains: Oils and fats Oil, fats or butter added to food or used for cooking, including extracted oils from nuts, fruits and seeds; and all animal fat
Foods made from grains: Sweets Sugary foods such as chocolates, candies, cookies and cakes/sweet biscuits and cakes, sweet pastries or ice cream
Antenatal and Postnatal Care for PLW
How many months pregnant are you? RECORD NUMBER OF COMPLETED MONTHS
Did you see anyone for antenatal care during your current/last pregnancy?
How many times did you seek antenatal care during your current/last pregnancy?
Whom did you visit for antenatal care during your current/last pregnancy? Anyone else? PROBE TO IDENTIFY EACH TYPE OF PERSON AND RECORD ALL MENTIONED.
Where did you receive antenatal care during your current/last pregnancy? Anywhere else?
During your current/last pregnancy, were you given an injection in the buttocks or your arm to prevent the baby from getting tetanus, that is, convulsions after birth?
How many times did you get a tetanus injection?
During your current/last pregnancy, were you given or did you buy any iron tablets or iron syrup? SHOW TABLETS/SYRUP (TAQWAI KHON PILLS).
If yes, for how many days did you take the tablets or syrup during the whole pregnancy? IF ANSWER IS NOT NUMERIC, PROBE FOR APPROXIMATE NUMBER OF DAYS.
During your current/last pregnancy, did you take any drug for intestinal worms?
When (NAME) was born, was he/she very large, larger than average, average, smaller than average, or very small?
How much did (NAME) weigh? RECORD WEIGHT IN KILOGRAMS FROM HEALTH CARD, IF AVAILABLE.

Who assisted with the delivery of (NAME)?Anyone else?Probe for the type(s) of person(s) and record all mentioned. If respondent says no one assisted, probe to determine whether any adult(s) were present at the delivery.
Where did you give birth to (NAME)? Probe to identify the type of source. If unable to determine if public or private sector, write the name of place.
How many times did you receive postnatal care during current/last pregnancy?
How many hours, days or weeks after the birth of (NAME) did the first check take place? If less than one day, record hours. If less than one week, record days.
Who checked on (NAME)'s health at that time? PROBE FOR MOST QUALIFIED PERSON
Where did this first check of (NAME) take place? Probe to identify the type of source. If unable to determine if public or private sector, write the name of place
How long after birth did you first put (NAME) to the breast?
Did you feed first milk (colostrum) to the child?
Why you did not feed colostrum to (name)?
Was (NAME) given anything to drink before breast milk?
What was (name) given to drink? Probe: Anything else? ‘Not given anything to drink’ (99) can only be recorded if no other response category is recorded. [Multiple responses]
Was (NAME) breastfed yesterday during the day or at night?

Sometimes babies are fed breast milk in different ways, for example by spoon, cup or bottle. This can happen when the mother cannot always be with her baby. Sometimes babies are breastfed by another woman, or given breast milk from another woman by spoon, cup or bottle or some other way. This can happen if a mother cannot breastfeed her own baby. Did (NAME) consume breast milk in any of these ways yesterday during the day or at night?
Now I would like to ask you about some medicines and vitamins that are sometimes given to infants was (NAME) given any vitamin drops or other medicines as drops yesterday during the day or at night?
Was (NAME) given [LOCAL NAME FOR ORS] yesterday during the day or at night?

Read the questions below. Read the list of liquids one by one and mark yes or no, ACCORDINGLY. After you have completed the list, continue by asking question 11 (see far right hand column) for those ITEMS (10B, 10C, And/or 10F) where the respondent replied ‘Yes’.

Next I would like to ask you about some liquids that (NAME) may have had yesterday during the day or at night. Did (NAME) have any (ITEM FORM LIST)? READ THE LIST OF LIQUIDS STARTING WITH ‘PLAN WATER’ READ QUESTION FOR ITEMS B,C, AND F IF CHILD CONSUMED THE ITEM RECORD ‘98’ FOR DON’T KNOW.
Infant formula? (If Yes Number of times)
Milk such as tinned, powdered, or fresh animal milk? (If Yes Number of times)
Any other liquids such as [list other water based liquids available in the local setting]?
Please describe everything that (NAME) ate yesterday during the day or night, whether at home or outside the home. If all ‘No’  go to 13 If at least one ‘yes’ or all ‘DK’  go to 14
Porridge, bread, rice, noodles, or other foods made from grains
Pumpkin, carrots , squash, or sweet potatoes that are yellow or orange inside
White potatoes, white yams manioc, cassava, or any other food made from roots
Liver, kidney , heart, or other organ meats

Fresh or dried fish, shellfish, or seafood

Cheese, yogurt, or other milk products

Did (NAME) eat any solid, semi- solid, or soft foods yesterday during the day or at night? Go back to Q.12 and record foods eaten. Then continue with Q.14 IF ‘YES’ PROBE: what kind of solid, semi-solid, or soft foods did (NAME) eat?

What did (name) drink from the bottle with a nipple?
Who advised you to use infant formula milk?

Child Immunization, Morbidity and Care Seeking
Do you have a card where (NAME)'s vaccinations are written down? If yes, may I see it please?

Did (NAME) ever have any vaccinations to prevent him/her from getting diseases, including vaccinations received in a national immunization day campaign?
COPY DATES FROM THE CARD. WRITE ‘44' IN ‘DAY' COLUMN IF CARD SHOWS THAT A DOSE WAS GIVEN, BUT NO DATE IS RECORDED.
Dates are not applicable if the source of vaccination is from maternal recall, and in response of card not seen or No card in Q.1
BCG against tuberculosis in the arm or shoulder
POLIO 0 (At birth), drops in the mouth
POLIO 1, first two weeks after birth
DPT/PENTA 1, an injection given in the thigh at 6 weeks:
DPT/PENTA 2, an injection given in the thigh at 10 weeks:
DPT/PENTA 3, an injection given in the thigh at 14 weeks
PCV 1: an injection in the thigh to prevent from pneumonia at 6 wks
PCV 2: an injection in the thigh to prevent from pneumonia at 10 wks
PCV 3: an injection in the thigh to prevent from pneumonia at 14 wks:
MEASLES 1: a shot in the arm at 9 months
MEASLES 2: a shot in the arm at 15 months
VITAMIN A: given within the last six months

Did the child (NAME) have any of the following illnesses during the last two weeks?
[PROMT FOR EACH AND RECORD] Any other illnesses?
Did you seek any care for these illnesses during the last two weeks?
Whom did you see for the illness (s) in the last two weeks? Anyone else? [PROBE TO IDENTIFY EACH TYPE OF PERSON AND RECORD ALL MENTIONED]
Where did you receive care for your child during the last two weeks?Anywhere else?
What is the first food a newborn baby should receive?
When a child should ideally be initiated breastfeeding after birth?
Have you heard about exclusive breastfeeding?
What do you mean by exclusive breastfeeding?
It means that the infant gets only breastmilk and no other liquids or foods
How long should a child receive nothing more than breastmilk?
What are the benefits for a child if he or she receives only breastmilk during the first six months of life?
Protection from diarrhea and other infections
Protection against obesity and chronic diseases in adulthood
How long is it recommended that a woman breastfeeds her child?
How long after birth a child should start to receive solid, semi-solid or soft foods in addition to breastmilk?
How many times a child should receive solid, semi-solid or soft foods in one day (day or at night)?
Which type of foods or food groups should a child eat on daily basis during 6-23 months of age?
Flesh foods (meat, fish, poultry and liver/organ meats)

1. The respondent of this survey should be a pregnant and lactating women with children 0-23 months of age in each selected household, 2. Introduce yourself and explain the purpose of study, 3. Consent should be obtained from the respondent before the interview, 4. In response of “No” or “Don’t know” follow the skip section.
